The Ingestion Pipeline (Write Path)
Distributed Crawler Infrastructure: A fleet of workers continuously polling registered RSS endpoints, sitemaps, and raw HTML pages. 
It manages polite crawling rates using a centralized coordinator (like Apache ZooKeeper) to ensure individual news servers are not overloaded.
Message Broker (Apache Kafka): Incoming raw article payloads are published to a Kafka topic. This acts as a buffer to protect downstream parsing engines 
from sudden spikes during major breaking news cycles.
Parser & Normalizer Service: Consumes from Kafka, strips away messy HTML boilerplate (ads, navbars), and structures the clean content into a standardized 
JSON format: title, author, body_text, publish_timestamp, and source_url.

2. Processing & Storage Layer
Primary Document Store (e.g., MongoDB or Amazon DynamoDB): Stores the raw, structured article records. This data layer is heavily partition-keyed on publish_date
to make old news archiving straightforward.
Search Index (Elasticsearch / OpenSearch): Ingests the article tokens to support fast text-based keyword search across topics, locations, and organizations.

3.3. Topic Clustering & Deduplication (The Intelligence Layer)
An aggregator becomes messy if 50 different outlets publish the exact same Associated Press wire article on your homepage.
Exact Deduplication: Compute an MD5 or SHA-256 hash of the cleaned article body. If the hash matches an entry already in the primary database from the last 24 hours, 
discard the duplicate or link it as a syndication.
Near-Deduplication (MinHash / LSH): For articles that are almost identical but have minor text edits, we use a MinHash algorithm combined with Locality-Sensitive Hashing (LSH)
to identify high Jaccard similarity scores without running expensive $O(N^2)$ comparisons.
Semantic Clustering (Vector DB Component): To group different articles covering the same event (e.g., BBC writing about a launch and CNN writing about the same launch), 
pass the text through an embedding model. Store the resulting embeddings in a vector store like pgvector or Qdrant. 
Run an online clustering algorithm (like Leader-Driven Clustering) to group incoming vector points into unique "Story IDs" based on cosine similarity thresholds.

Feed Generation & Personalization (Read Path)
Generating a feed on demand for every user visit is computationally expensive due to the matrix multiplications required for machine-learning-based rankings. 
Instead, we compute feeds asynchronously using a Hybrid Fan-Out Strategy.
[ New Grouped Story ] ---> [ Fan-Out Worker ] ---> [ Compute Rank Score ] 
                                                           |
                                                           v
[ User Active Feed ] <--- [ Read Cache ] <--- [ Append to Redis Min-Heap ]

1. Pre-Computing Global Hotness
For anonymous users or generic categories (e.g., "Technology"), a background worker pre-calculates standard trending feeds every 60 seconds.

2. Personalized Fan-Out
For authenticated users with specific preferences:When a high-impact story cluster is formed, a worker identifies which user segments or topic tags
match this content.The system computes a personalized match score and inserts the story ID into the user's dedicated feed cache—stored as a Redis Sorted Set (ZSET), 
where the score is the computed ranking value.When the user opens the app, the system fetches their pre-computed ZSET from Redis in O(log N + M) time, resulting in sub-50ms render latencies.
A Redis ZSET is powered by a dual-structure architecture: a Hash Table combined with a Skip List
Phase 1: The $O(log N)$ Search StepRedis uses the skip list's higher express lanes to fast-travel across the dataset. It compares your query constraints against
the nodes until it pinpoints the exact starting element of your requested range.Because it skips exponentially large groups of elements at each step, 
finding this starting point scales logarithmically with the total size of the user's feed (N).
Phase 2: The O(M) Retrieval StepOnce Redis has used the express lanes to drop its pointer directly onto the correct starting node at the bottom layer, 
it drops down to the base linked list.From there, it doesn't need to jump anymore. It simply walks sequentially along the pointers from left to right, collecting 
exactly M elements (the specific chunk size you requested, such as the top 20 stories for Page 1 of the feed). Collecting M items sequentially takes 
linear time relative to the page size: $O(M)$.
Why this Matters for System DesignWhen designing high-throughput systems like a news feed, 
this mathematical distinction is critical:N is the Total Feed Volume: A user might have $1,000$ stories total stored in their backlog pool (N=1000). Because log_2(1000) approx 10, 
finding the start of the page requires only about 10 computational hops.M is the Page Size: You only return 20 items to the mobile screen (M=20).Because O(log N) is extremely small and flat, 
and $M$ is tightly bounded by pagination limits, the overall operation completes in a fraction of a millisecond.

Handling System Constraints & Key Challenges
How to Scale Metadata Filtering
  If a user changes their feed settings to "Show me breaking news from the US, but filter out anything related to sports," a naive vector search can break or return poor results.
  
  The Architecture Choice: Use a database configuration that supports single-stage/native filtering (like Qdrant or pgvector with structured indexes). This ensures the metadata 
  constraint (Category != Sports) is checked during the graph traversal step of the vector search, guaranteeing you get back the correct number of relevant results without losing graph connectivity.

The Embedding Model Upgrades Pitfall
  If you decide to upgrade your internal topic categorization embedding model from an old version to a faster, highly precise new model, your existing vector database index instantly becomes incompatible.
  
  The Migration Pattern: You must spin up a parallel vector database cluster. Write a migration script that reads the raw historical articles from your primary Document DB, runs them through the new
  embedding model, and populates the new vector index. Keep both paths running in parallel, perform an A/B test on your clustering accuracy, and 
  then switch your API Gateway traffic over before tearing down the old vector database cluster.
